The paper discusses multi-agent reinforcement learning in sequential social dilemmas, which involves the use of deep Q-networks to learn policies that implement strategic intentions. This topic is closely related to several sub-categories of computer science, including machine learning (cs.LG), artificial intelligence (cs.AI), game theory (cs.GT), multi-agent systems (cs.MA), and control systems (cs.SY). Given the focus on reinforcement learning and deep Q-networks, cs.LG and cs.AI are the most likely sub-categories. However, the emphasis on social dilemmas and game theory suggests that cs.GT and cs.MA are also relevant. Finally, the use of Markov games and analysis of environmental factors suggests a connection to control systems, hence cs.SY is also a possible sub-category.
